ictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Dominique, Edrice, Evens, Guerline, Jean-Claude, Kettly, Marthe, Monique, Murielle, Serge, Yves.","French, Breton (mainly Finistère), and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the French personal name <i>Blaise</i>, from Latin   Blasius  . Compare   Blaize   1.","Scottish (Ayrshire and Bute): variant of   Blaize   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Blaes","meanings":["German (Saarland; also <b>Bläs</b>): from a French-influenced (see   Blaise  ) vernacular form of the personal name   Blasius  . Compare   Blas  .","Dutch: variant of   Blees  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Blaize","meanings":["French and Breton: variant of   Blaise   1. In France, this surname is most common in Brittany (Finistère).","English (Staffordshire): from Middle English <i>blase</i>, <i>blese</i>, <i>bleis</i> ‘torch, firebrand’, perhaps also used for a torch maker or bearer.","English (Staffordshire): alternatively, a variant of   Bloise  ."]},{"name":"Blais","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Normand, Andre, Emile, Fernand, Lucien, Aime, Gilles, Julien, Michel, Yvon, Alphonse.","French: variant of   Blaise  . Compare   Blair   and   Blay  .","History: Pierre Blais from Hanc in Deux-Sèvres, France, married first Anne Perrault in Sainte-Famille, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1669, and second Élisabeth Royer in Saint-Jean, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1689. — In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Joseph Tousignant <i>dit</i> Blais, a descendant of Pierre Tousignant (see   Tousignant  ). He married Marie Charpentier in Baie-du-Febvre, QC, in 1835."]},{"name":"Blaze","meanings":["English: variant of   Blaise   2. See also   Blaize   2."]},{"name":"Blasius","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Ireneusz, Iwona, Jerzy, Jozefa, Krzysztof, Mieczyslaw, Miroslaw, Wieslaw, Wlodzimierz, Zofia, Zosia.","Polish (<b>Błaszczyk</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Błażej</i>, from Latin   Blasius  ."]},{"name":"Blease","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): probably a variant of   Blaise  ."]}]},{"name":"Marguerite","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Margaret  , also used in the English-speaking world, where its use has been reinforced by the fact that the name was adopted in the 19th century for a garden flower, a large cultivated variety of daisy. <i>Margaret</i> was earlier used in English as a dialect word denoting the ox-eye daisy, and the French equivalent was borrowed into English just in time to catch the vogue for deriving girls' names from vocabulary words denoting flowers.  See also  Daisy ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Marguerite Blaise was born in 1700. She married Nicholas Grandadam in 1730. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. She died in 1751, at the age of 51."},"et":{"Abt 1700–Bef 1751":"1700–1751","1698–Male":"1698–Surnud","1729–1805":"1729–1805","–Female":"Surnud","1700–1751":"1700–1751","1700":"1700","1698":"1698","Bef 1751":"1751","1751":"1751","Abt 1700":"1700","1729":"1729","12 March 1729":"12. märts 1729","Bef 1730":"1730","1805":"1805","Alsace, France":"Alsace, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1700–Bef 1751":"1700–1751","1698–Male":"1698–Kuollut","1729–1805":"1729–1805","–Female":"Kuollut","1700–1751":"1700–1751","1700":"1700","1698":"1698","Bef 1751":"1751","1751":"1751","Abt 1700":"1700","1729":"1729","12 March 1729":"12. maaliskuuta 1729","Bef 1730":"1730","1805":"1805","Alsace, France":"Alsace, Ranska"},"fr":{"Abt 1700–Bef 1751":"1700–1751","1698–Male":"1698–Décédé","1729–1805":"1729–1805","–Female":"Décédée","1700–1751":"1700–1751","1700":"1700","1698":"1698","Bef 1751":"1751","1751":"1751","Abt 1700":"1700","1729":"1729","12 March 1729":"12 mars 1729","Bef 1730":"1730","1805":"1805","Alsace, France":"Alsac